      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Numerical solver error' factor as a distinct assessment category from 'Numerical code verification' and 'Discretization error' pertains specifically to iterative convergence errors and floating-point round-off accumulation that are separately tracked in certain high-fidelity aerospace and nuclear simulation frameworks (e.g., NASA CFD validation programs and NRC reactor safety analysis protocols). In the ASME V&V 40-2018 MRL 2 framework for medical device CFD, iterative convergence is subsumed within the Discretization error factor assessment: residual convergence to below 1×10⁻⁶ on all transport equations is documented as part of the GCI study protocol, and round-off error is negligible for double-precision computation on the mesh sizes employed (18.4M cells, double precision throughout). The FDA's 2021 Computational Modeling guidance and the ASME V&V 40-2018 standard do not enumerate 'Numerical solver error' as a standalone factor separate from discretization error at MRL 2 for rotating machinery hemolysis CFD. Treating it as a separate assessable factor would constitute double-counting of evidence already captured under Discretization error (GCI study, convergence documentation). Accordingly, this factor is designated not-applicable to avoid artificial inflation of the factor count while all substantive solver-error concerns are addressed within the Discretization error and Software quality assurance assessments."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Use error' factor addresses the risk that an analyst applies the model outside its validated domain or misinterprets model outputs in a clinical or operational deployment context. This factor is primarily relevant for models that will be operated by end-users who are not the model developers — for example, a CFD solver deployed as a clinical decision-support tool where non-expert users interact with the model directly. In the present COU, the CFD model is operated exclusively by the credentialed biofluid mechanics team that developed and validated it, under a controlled simulation protocol with mandatory peer review of all simulation setups before execution. The model outputs (NIH, RHI) are interpreted by the same engineering team that conducted the validation and are not exposed to clinical end-users. FDA guidance on computational modeling (2021) identifies use error as a concern for patient-facing software tools and interactive clinical decision support, not for engineering analysis tools operated under controlled laboratory protocols. At MRL 2 for a Class II device with medium model influence, the risk of consequential use error is further mitigated by the independent testing that confirms model results before regulatory submission. Therefore, use error does not constitute a credibility risk pathway for this COU and is designated not-applicable."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Model form' factor as a standalone credibility assessment item addresses the selection and justification of the mathematical model structure — turbulence closure, constitutive relations, governing equation set — relative to the physics of the COU. At MRL 2, ASME V&V 40-2018 Table 3 does not require a separate Model form assessment; the adequacy of model form is instead demonstrated through the Output comparison and Relevance of validation activities factors, which together confirm that the chosen RANS k-ω SST turbulence model with Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power law produces predictions within acceptable tolerance of experimental data across the COU operating envelope. A separate Model form assessment would require independent physics-based justification of the turbulence closure selection (e.g., DNS or LES comparison studies) that exceeds the evidence requirements at MRL 2 for a Class II device. The model-form uncertainty is quantified within the Output comparison validation uncertainty estimate (±15% inter-model spread between G-W and Bludszuweit models), providing the necessary evidence without requiring a standalone factor assessment. Designating this factor not-applicable at MRL 2 is consistent with the ASME V&V 40-2018 framework, which reserves standalone model form assessment for MRL 3 and above where higher-fidelity physics justification is required."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Model inputs' factor as a distinct credibility item addresses the characterization of uncertain or variable input parameters — material properties, boundary condition distributions, geometric variability — and their propagation through the model to the QoI. At MRL 2 for this COU, input parameter sensitivity is addressed through two existing assessed factors: (1) the Test conditions factor, which documents the traceability and uncertainty of all boundary conditions applied in the CFD model, and (2) the Relevance of quantities of interest factor, which includes a sensitivity analysis confirming that NIH is monotonically sensitive to the geometric tolerance variations under evaluation. A standalone Model inputs assessment at MRL 2 would require formal uncertainty propagation (e.g., Monte Carlo or polynomial chaos expansion across the full input space) that is not mandated by ASME V&V 40-2018 at this risk level. The input uncertainties that are material to the COU decision (flow rate ±0.1 L/min, rotational speed ±10 RPM, tip clearance ±0.1 mm) are bounded within the operating envelope and their effect on NIH is captured in the validation uncertainty estimate. Designating Model inputs not-applicable avoids redundant documentation of evidence already captured in Test conditions and QoI relevance assessments, consistent with MRL 2 scoping practice."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Test samples' factor addresses the representativeness of physical test articles used in validation experiments — specifically whether the samples tested are geometrically, materially, and functionally representative of the device population to be covered by the model predictions. This factor is most consequential when there is significant device-to-device manufacturing variability or when prototype test articles differ substantially from production devices. In the present COU, the validation experiments use the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump, which is a standardized reference geometry with published nominal dimensions and no device-to-device variability (it is a defined reference artifact, not a manufactured production device). The geometric tolerance sensitivity being evaluated by the CFD model is precisely the variation being studied, not a source of uncontrolled test sample variability. Furthermore, the hemolysis experiments use fresh ovine blood from a controlled blood bank supply with documented hematocrit and plasma hemoglobin baseline, meeting ASTM F1841 sample preparation requirements. There is no meaningful test sample representativeness question that is not already addressed by the Test conditions and Equivalency of input parameters factors. Accordingly, Test samples is designated not-applicable for this COU at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor evaluates whether the input parameters used in the computational model match those of the physical validation experiments with sufficient fidelity to support valid comparison. This factor is particularly important when validation experiments are conducted on surrogate fluids, scaled geometries, or under conditions that differ from the COU and require equivalency arguments (e.g., Reynolds number scaling, Womersley number matching). In the present COU, the validation experiments are conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at full scale under the same operating conditions (flow rates, rotational speeds) as the COU operating points, using a glycerol-water analogue fluid whose viscosity is matched to blood viscosity at the relevant shear rates (0.0035 Pa·s at high shear). There is no scaling, surrogate geometry, or fluid substitution that requires an equivalency argument beyond what is documented in the Test conditions factor. The one-to-one correspondence between CFD inputs and experimental conditions eliminates the need for a separate equivalency assessment. This factor is therefore not-applicable for this COU, as the conditions under which it would add credibility evidence (surrogate testing, geometric scaling, or fluid substitution) do not arise in this validation program."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cpb-hemolysis-mrl2-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-biofluid-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The CFD model for CPB hemolysis prediction is accepted as credible for the stated COU at MRL 2 based on the following structured evidence: (1) All 7 assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels — Software QA (achieved 2, required 1), Numerical code verification (achieved 2, required 1), Discretization error (achieved 3, required 2), Test conditions (achieved 2, required 2), Output comparison (achieved 2, required 2), Relevance of QoI (achieved 3, required 2), Relevance of validation activities (achieved 2, required 2). No factor shortfall exists. (2) The 6 factors designated not-applicable (Numerical solver error, Use error, Model form, Model inputs, Test samples, Equivalency of input parameters) each carry documented rationale explaining why the factor does not constitute a credibility risk pathway for this specific COU at MRL 2. The rationale for each is grounded in the ASME V&V 40-2018 MRL 2 scoping guidance and confirmed by the absence of the risk conditions that would make each factor material. (3) Validation evidence (PIV velocity comparison, in-vitro RHI comparison, GCI mesh convergence study) provides a complete provenance chain from foundational experimental datasets through quantified uncertainty to the primary QoI. All ValidationResult objects carry comparedAgainst, prov:wasGeneratedBy, and hasUncertaintyQuantification links. (4) The model correctly identifies the worst-case hemolysis operating condition (6 L/min, 3500 RPM) in 5 of 5 experimental comparisons, which is the primary purpose of the COU. The RH < 1 acceptance criterion is met relative to the predicate device at all 5 operating points. (5) Sensitivity analysis confirms NIH is monotonically sensitive to tip clearance variation over the tolerance range of interest, supporting the model's fitness for the geometric tolerance evaluation purpose. The combined weight of evidence supports acceptance of the model for regulatory submission in support of the Class II CPB device 510(k).",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
